        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Imaging requirements:
The emitting regions in these galaxies are reasonably small, with extents (estimated from our CO(1-0) map; Fig 3a) of up to 17'' in each velocity channel. We thus request observations with a resolution of 1.4'' (C34-3 array configuration), to ensure we adequately resolve the sources. Such a resolution is also well matched to that of our optical IFU data, allowing direct comparison. The maximum angular scale for the array in this configuration is 18'', larger than our sources, ensuring that we will not resolve out flux and do not need ACA observations. Our main science goal is to resolve ``subclump" regions outside the galaxy nuclei (red boxed regions in Fig 3a), which have a typical FWHM of 80 km/s in the CO map which will require a spectral resolution of 30 km/s in order to resolve them by a factor of three and resolve the nuclear emission region with a FWHM of 300 km/s by a factor of ~10.  

In order to show that the requested configuration will be able to fulfill our science goals  we created mock observations by scaling the CO maps presented in Fig 3a to the HCN line flux that we wish to detect in each galaxy using values from our IRAM spectra in Fig 2. These were then input to the CASA ALMA simulator (including the effect of the atmosphere with 5.1 mm PWV) and the results are shown in Fig 3b. We clearly detect the sources and do not resolve out flux, showing that our proposed sensitivity and array configuration are well chosen. We have excellent UV coverage even in these short integrations, showing that the Cycle 2 capabilities are ideal for this project.
 
 Correlator setup:
As described above, we aim to map the transitions of HCN, HCO+, HNC, and CCH in each of the galaxies, as they trace different density components and photodissociation. We also select shock tracers H2CO, Methanol, and SO2 lines to look for a detection at no extra cost time-wise to our science goals. 
The velocity widths of the lines in question vary between 80 and 300 km/s. We thus propose to use the 1875 MHz basebands (spectral averaged by a factor of 2 to reduce the data rate) to achieve a resolution of 3.3 km/s for which we can further bin up to 10 km/s to ensure we have ~10 channels over the emitting regions. 

Requested sensitivity:
Detecting all 4 of these transitions in NGC 4568 and at least HCN/HCO+ in NGC 4567 (HCN/CCH not detected in IRAM 30m data) is required for our science goals (see Fig 2). Hence we estimate the time required to map the weakest transition detected in the galaxy pair, based on fluxes from our IRAM-30m observations in Table 1 (see also Fig 2). We specify the required sensitivity in order to ensure a 5 sigma detection of the weakest line per synthesized beam in each channel (see Table 1, Fig 2).  This will also give us the power to unbin the data around the strongest lines in order to get better constraints on the velocity structure of the material along each line-of-sight. For NGC 4567/8, the weakest line detected is HCO+ at 7.2 mJy, requiring a sensitivity limit of 1.4 mJy. The ALMA OT suggests reaching the flux limits in Table 1 for the highest frequency line in each setup, with the standard 5.2mm PWV, 34 antennas in the C34-3 array configuration and a velocity channel width of 3 km/s will require a total time request of only 2.7 hours.  In comparison, reaching the same sensitivity and coverage with CARMA on these objects would take at least a factor of 10 times longer, highlighting why we require ALMA to reach our science goals.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
